      <strong>Tip:</strong> Buy one extra bag per 10 posts. Holes are never perfectly cylindrical — rocky soil or loose walls mean you consistently need slightly more than calculated.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none text-gray-700 print:prose-sm">

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-5">How to Use This Quikrete Bags Calculator</h2>
    <p>Follow these five steps to get an accurate material estimate for your fencing project.</p>
    <ol class="space-y-3 list-decimal list-inside">
      <li><strong>Use the Post Size Quick-Select:</strong> Start by selecting your post type (e.g., 4x4 or 6x6). This will auto-fill the "Post Width" (actual size) and input a "Hole Diameter" based on industry-standard recommendations. You can adjust the hole diameter manually if necessary.</li>
      <li><strong>Set the Hole Depth:</strong> Adjust the hole depth based on your planned fence height and local frost lines. The standard rule of thumb is that fence post holes should be dug to a depth equal to one-third ($1/3$) to one-half ($1/2$) of the above-ground height of the post. Regardless of fence height, 24 inches is generally considered the absolute minimum depth for stability.</li>
      <li><strong>Enter Total Number of Posts:</strong> Input how many posts are in your fence run.</li>
      <li><strong>Select Bag Size:</strong> Choose which specific product you intend to buy. Note that while 80 lb bags generally provide the best financial value for larger projects, 50 lb Fast-Setting bags are significantly easier to handle if you are working solo.</li>
      <li><strong>Select Concrete Type:</strong> Choose between "Standard Mix" or "Fast-Setting." After clicking calculate, scroll down to the results to find specific installation instructions tailored to that concrete type.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-5">The Formula</h2>
    <p>This calculator determines the net volume of concrete required by calculating the volume of the dug hole (cylinder) and subtracting the volume of the post being inserted (rectangular prism). All dimensional inputs (inches) are converted to feet for the final calculation.</p>
    
    <p class="font-mono text-sm bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg print:bg-white print:border print:border-gray-200">
      Hole Volume = $\pi \times radius^2 \times depth$ (in feet)<br>
      Post Volume = $actualWidth^2 \times depth$ (in feet)<br>
      Bags Per Post = Net Volume / Bag Yield (rounded up to next whole bag)
    </p>

    <p>We use specific product yield data provided by Quikrete for high-strength concrete mixes to ensure accuracy:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>50 lb bag:</strong> Yields 0.375 cubic feet.</li>
      <li><strong>60 lb bag:</strong> Yields 0.45 cubic feet.</li>
      <li><strong>80 lb bag:</strong> Yields 0.60 cubic feet.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-5">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">How many 80 lb bags of Quikrete for a standard 4x4 fence post in a 10 inch hole at 24 inches deep?</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600">You need **2 bags** (80 lb) for this specific scenario. While the raw net volume is roughly 0.925 cubic feet, one 80 lb bag only yields 0.6 cubic feet. You must purchase two bags, even though you won't use the full second bag.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Should I use Fast-Setting or standard Quikrete for fence posts?</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600">For most homeowners, Fast-Setting Quikrete is superior for setting fence posts because it requires no mixing in a wheelbarrow. You set the post, pour the dry concrete from the bag into the hole, and add water on top. Standard concrete is slightly stronger and often cheaper, but requires labor-intensive pre-mixing before pouring.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">How long to wait before attaching fence panels to Fast-Setting versus standard concrete?</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600">If using Fast-Setting Quikrete, you can generally begin attaching fence panels or loading the post in **4 hours**. For standard concrete mixes, you should wait at least **24 to 48 hours** for the concrete to properly cure before subjecting the post to any load.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">How much water to add per bag of Quikrete?</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600">If using standard mix (mixed beforehand), you need approximately 3 quarts of water per 80 lb bag. If using Fast-Setting concrete (dry pour method), you don't use a specific measured amount; you pour water onto the dry mix until the mix is completely saturated.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Do Sakrete and other brands use the same bag yields as Quikrete?</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600">Yes, generally. Pre-mix concrete is sold based on standard weights and industry-standard yields. An 80 lb bag of standard high-strength concrete mix will yield approximately 0.6 cubic feet, whether it is branded as Quikrete, Sakrete, or a generic store brand.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Do I need to mix Quikrete Fast-Setting or just pour it dry?</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600">Just pour it dry. This is the intended "no-mix" method for setting fence posts or mailbox posts. You level the post, fill the hole with the dry Fast-Setting mix, then saturate it thoroughly with water. The water percolates through the dry mix, initiating the curing process without manual mixing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-5">Related Calculators</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-5 not-prose mb-12 print:hidden">
      <a href="/calculators/concrete-fence-post" class="block bg-white p-5 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 hover:border-blue-500 hover:shadow-md transition-all">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1 text-base">Concrete Fence Post Calculator</h4>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-xs">If you are hiring a truck and just need the raw cubic yards of concrete, use this version.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/calculators/concrete-slab" class="block bg-white p-5 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 hover:border-blue-500 hover:shadow-md transition-all">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1 text-base">Concrete Slab Calculator</h4>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-xs">Calculate how many bags you need for patios, footings, or walkways, or estimate yards for a concrete truck.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/calculators/rebar" class="block bg-white p-5 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 hover:border-blue-500 hover:shadow-md transition-all">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1 text-base">Rebar Calculator</h4>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-xs">Calculate lengths, pieces, weight, and tie wire needed for structural concrete reinforcement.</p>
      </a>
    </div>

  </div>

</Layout>

<script is:inline>
  function getNum(id) {
    return parseFloat(document.getElementById(id).value) || 0;
  }

  function toFt(ftId, inId) {
    return getNum(ftId) + getNum(inId) / 12;
  }

  function applyPostPreset() {
    var val = document.getElementById('post_preset').value;
    if (!val) return;
    var parts = val.split(',');
    document.getElementById('post_size').value = parts[0];
    document.getElementById('hole_dia').value = parts[1];
    calculate();
  }

  function calcBagsForSize(netVolCuFt, bagYield) {
    return Math.ceil(netVolCuFt / bagYield);
  }

  function calculate() {
    var holeDiaIn = getNum('hole_dia');
    var holeDepthFt = toFt('hole_depth_ft', 'hole_depth_in');
    var postSizeIn = getNum('post_size') || 3.5;
    var numPosts = getNum('num_posts');

    document.getElementById('errorMsg').classList.add('hidden');

    if (holeDiaIn <= 0 || holeDepthFt <= 0 || numPosts <= 0) {
      document.getElementById('results').classList.add('hidden');
      if (holeDiaIn > 0 || holeDepthFt > 0) {
        document.getElementById('errorMsg').classList.remove('hidden');
      }
      return;
    }

    // Hole volume — cylinder
    var holeRadFt = (holeDiaIn / 2) / 12;
    var holeVolCuFt = Math.PI * holeRadFt * holeRadFt * holeDepthFt;

    // Post volume — square post
    var postSizeFt = postSizeIn / 12;
    var postVolCuFt = postSizeFt * postSizeFt * holeDepthFt;

    // Net concrete volume per post
    var netVolPerPost = Math.max(holeVolCuFt - postVolCuFt, 0);
    var totalNetVol = netVolPerPost * numPosts;

    // Selected bag
    var bagYield = parseFloat(document.getElementById('bag_size').value) || 0.60;
    var bagSizeLabel = bagYield === 0.375 ? '50 lb' : bagYield === 0.45 ? '60 lb' : '80 lb';
    var bagWeightLb = bagYield === 0.375 ? 50 : bagYield === 0.45 ? 60 : 80;

    var bagsPerPost = calcBagsForSize(netVolPerPost, bagYield);
    var totalBags = Math.ceil(totalNetVol / bagYield);
    var totalWeightLb = totalBags * bagWeightLb;

    // Comparison all three sizes
    var bags50 = Math.ceil(totalNetVol / 0.375);
    var bags60 = Math.ceil(totalNetVol / 0.45);
    var bags80 = Math.ceil(totalNetVol / 0.60);

    var comparisonHTML =
      '50 lb bags: ' + bags50 + ' bags (' + (bags50 * 50).toLocaleString() + ' lbs total)<br>' +
      '60 lb bags: ' + bags60 + ' bags (' + (bags60 * 60).toLocaleString() + ' lbs total)<br>' +
      '80 lb bags: ' + bags80 + ' bags (' + (bags80 * 80).toLocaleString() + ' lbs total)';

    var concreteType = document.getElementById('concrete_type').value;
    var methodText = concreteType === 'fastsetting'
      ? 'Fast-Setting (50 lb): Set post, pour dry mix into hole, add water slowly. Do NOT pre-mix. Sets in 20-40 minutes — brace and level post immediately. Can attach fence panels in 4 hours.'
      : 'Standard Mix: Mix per bag instructions in bucket or wheelbarrow. Pour in 6-inch layers, rod each layer to remove air pockets. Crown top slightly above grade so water drains away. Wait 24-48 hours before loading.';

    document.getElementById('results').classList.remove('hidden');
    document.getElementById('r_vol_per_post').textContent = netVolPerPost.toFixed(3) + ' cu ft';
    document.getElementById('r_bags_per_post').textContent = bagsPerPost + ' × ' + bagSizeLabel;
    document.getElementById('r_total_bags').textContent = totalBags + ' bags';
    document.getElementById('r_total_weight').textContent = totalWeightLb.toLocaleString() + ' lbs';
    document.getElementById('r_comparison').innerHTML = comparisonHTML;
    document.getElementById('r_method').textContent = methodText;
  }

  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
    document.querySelectorAll('input[type="number"]').forEach(function (el) {
      el.addEventListener('input', calculate);
    });
    document.getElementById('bag_size').addEventListener('change', calculate);
    document.getElementById('concrete_type').addEventListener('change', calculate);
  });
</script>
